1.3 — New Doctrines Introduced in Part #5
DOCTRINE-028: RETENTION IS TIME-BOUND, POLICY-ENFORCED, AND NON-REVERSIBLE
  When a retention window expires for an Evidence Packet:
    - All detailed raw records (events, metadata, device info, connectivity)
      are PERMANENTLY DELETED by automated policy.
    - This is: time-bound, non-discretionary, non-reversible, no human approval.
    - There is NO mechanism to extend, pause, override, or restore deleted data.
  The retention window is configurable per facility (within system limits)
  but once data is deleted, it is GONE — even for the facility that owned it.

DOCTRINE-029: PROOF-OF-EXISTENCE SURVIVES CONTENT DELETION
  After retention expiry, the system retains EXCLUSIVELY:
    - The cryptographic hash of the complete Evidence Packet
    - The hash chain linking packets to maintain structural integrity
    - Minimal tombstone metadata (packet_code, expiry date, retention policy ID)
  NOTHING else survives:
    - No event content. No timestamps (beyond tombstone creation). No actors.
    - No annotations. No facility claims. No contextual events. No sessions.
  The system can answer ONE question after expiry:
    ‘Did an Evidence Packet with this exact hash exist, unchanged, at that time?’
  It cannot answer any other question.

DOCTRINE-030: EXPORTED EVIDENCE IS THE AUTHORITATIVE CONTENT CARRIER
  Human-readable evidence content (timelines, events, narratives) lives in the
  EXPORTED Evidence Packet (PDF), NOT in the platform after retention expiry.
  Therefore:
    - Evidence Packets must be exportable as self-contained PDF artifacts.
    - PDFs must embed the hash, verification instructions, and a complete
      human-readable record of all events in the session.
    - PDFs must be readable and verifiable WITHOUT network access.
    - PDFs must survive EvidenceLedger being offline, sold, or dissolved.

DOCTRINE-031: HASH ANCHORING ENABLES PLATFORM-ABSENT VERIFICATION
  For an Evidence Packet to remain verifiable when EvidenceLedger is absent,
  its hash must be ANCHORED to an independent, platform-external source.
  EvidenceLedger provides multiple anchoring mechanisms:
    (A) Public hash registry — published periodically (e.g., daily digest)
        as a static, versioned JSON file at a well-known URL.
    (B) Third-party publishing — facility exports their own copy of packet
        hashes for publication on their domain / compliance records.
    (C) Optional blockchain anchoring — where required by regulation or
        customer contract (NOT default; configurable and opt-in).
  At least one anchoring method MUST be active for every generated
  Evidence Packet before retention expiry.

DOCTRINE-032: POST-EXPIRY, THE SYSTEM IS A PASSIVE VERIFIER ONLY
  After retention expiry, EvidenceLedger’s operational role is reduced to:
    - Accepting a hash as input
    - Looking it up in the tombstone table
    - Returning a binary yes/no: ‘This hash was registered in our system
      prior to its retention expiry on DATE.’
  It CANNOT:
    - Reconstruct events, timelines, or any content
    - Provide additional metadata beyond the tombstone
    - Modify, reissue, or re-interpret anything
    - Accept requests to ‘recover’ expired data

DOCTRINE-033: EVIDENCELEDGER REMOVES ITSELF FROM THE TRUST CHAIN
  The system is architecturally designed to become UNNECESSARY after evidence
  creation. A court in 2040 evaluating a PDF from 2025 should be able to
  verify it using ONLY:
    (1) The PDF itself
    (2) A hash, independently published in 2025 (via anchoring)
    (3) Standard SHA-256 tooling (openssl, sha256sum, built-in OS tools)
  No EvidenceLedger contact, access, or trust is required for verification.
  This is the system’s ULTIMATE value proposition.
