SECTION 3 — THE RETENTION EXPIRY WORKER
The retention worker is a pg_cron-scheduled database function that runs daily. It identifies expired Evidence Packets, creates tombstones, and permanently deletes all associated detailed records. It runs as the system_lifecycle_worker role (DOCTRINE-005) — no human trigger is possible.
3.1 — Function: retention_expiry_daily_tick()
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION retention_expiry_daily_tick()
  RETURNS void AS $$
DECLARE
  v_packet RECORD;
  v_policy RECORD;
  v_start_time TIMESTAMPTZ;
  v_session_id UUID;
  v_event_count INTEGER;
  v_operation_code TEXT;
BEGIN
  v_start_time := NOW();

  -- Find all evidence packets whose scheduled_expiry_at <= NOW()
  -- and whose session still has associated events (i.e., not already tombstoned)
  FOR v_packet IN
    SELECT ep.*, s.facility_id
    FROM evidence_packets ep
    JOIN sessions s ON s.id = ep.session_id
    WHERE ep.scheduled_expiry_at <= NOW()
      AND NOT EXISTS (
        SELECT 1 FROM evidence_tombstones et WHERE et.packet_code = ep.packet_code
      )
  LOOP
    -- Load the active retention policy for this facility
    SELECT * INTO v_policy FROM retention_policies
      WHERE facility_id = v_packet.facility_id
        AND effective_until IS NULL
      LIMIT 1;

    v_session_id := v_packet.session_id;

    -- Count events before deletion (for audit)
    SELECT COUNT(*) INTO v_event_count
      FROM session_events WHERE session_id = v_session_id;

    -- STEP A: Generate unique operation code
    v_operation_code := 'RET-' || to_char(NOW(), 'YYYY-MM-DD') || '-' ||
                        to_char(EXTRACT(EPOCH FROM NOW()), 'FM999999');

    -- STEP B: Create the tombstone BEFORE deleting anything
    INSERT INTO evidence_tombstones (
      packet_code, packet_hash, session_hash, pdf_hash,
      facility_id, original_created_at, retention_expired_at,
      retention_policy_id, retention_months_at_deletion,
      anchoring_methods
    ) VALUES (
      v_packet.packet_code,
      v_packet.packet_hash,
      (SELECT session_hash FROM sessions WHERE id = v_session_id),
      v_packet.packet_data->>'pdf_hash',
      v_packet.facility_id,
      v_packet.generated_at,
      NOW(),
      v_policy.id,
      v_policy.retention_months,
      ARRAY['REGISTRY']  -- at least the daily digest
    );

    -- STEP C: Delete ALL detailed records for this session
    -- Order matters: delete child records first
    DELETE FROM session_context_events WHERE session_id = v_session_id;
    DELETE FROM facility_claims WHERE session_id = v_session_id;
    DELETE FROM session_events WHERE session_id = v_session_id;
    DELETE FROM sessions WHERE id = v_session_id;
    DELETE FROM evidence_packets WHERE id = v_packet.id;

    -- STEP D: Audit log entry
    INSERT INTO retention_audit_log (
      operation_code, retention_policy_id, facility_id,
      packet_count_deleted, event_count_deleted,
      tombstone_count_created,
      pre_operation_session_hash_chain, post_operation_tombstone_digest,
      deleted_packet_codes, execution_duration_ms
    ) VALUES (
      v_operation_code, v_policy.id, v_packet.facility_id,
      1, v_event_count, 1,
      v_packet.packet_hash,
      encode(sha256(convert_to(v_packet.packet_code || '::' || v_packet.packet_hash, 'UTF8')), 'hex'),
      ARRAY[v_packet.packet_code],
      EXTRACT(EPOCH FROM (NOW() - v_start_time))::INTEGER * 1000
    );
  END LOOP;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql SECURITY DEFINER
   SET search_path = public;  -- prevent search_path injection

-- Grant execute to system_lifecycle_worker ONLY
REVOKE ALL ON FUNCTION retention_expiry_daily_tick() FROM PUBLIC;
GRANT EXECUTE ON FUNCTION retention_expiry_daily_tick()
  TO system_lifecycle_worker;
3.2 — pg_cron Schedule
-- Schedule the retention worker to run daily at 03:00 UTC
-- (low-traffic period to minimize user impact)
SELECT cron.schedule(
  'retention-expiry-daily',
  '0 3 * * *',  -- daily at 03:00 UTC
  $$ SELECT retention_expiry_daily_tick(); $$
);
🪦 THE TOMBSTONE ORDERING IS CRITICAL
The order of operations in the retention worker is NON-NEGOTIABLE:

1. Create the tombstone FIRST (preserves hash).
2. Delete detailed records AFTER the tombstone exists.
3. Write audit log entry LAST.

If this order is reversed — if detailed records are deleted before the tombstone is created — a system crash during the operation could result in PERMANENT LOSS of both content AND proof-of-existence. The tombstone-first pattern ensures that even catastrophic failure mid-operation leaves the hash intact.

The entire loop body for each packet must run in a single transaction to ensure atomicity.


SECTION 4 — HASH ANCHORING (Registry Digests)
Hash anchoring ensures that packet hashes exist in independently-verifiable form OUTSIDE EvidenceLedger. Without anchoring, a party who only possesses an exported PDF cannot verify it against any external reference if EvidenceLedger is offline.
4.1 — Daily Digest Generator
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION generate_daily_hash_digest()
  RETURNS UUID AS $$
DECLARE
  v_period_start TIMESTAMPTZ;
  v_period_end TIMESTAMPTZ;
  v_digest_id UUID;
  v_digest_code TEXT;
  v_manifest JSONB;
  v_merkle_root TEXT;
  v_packet_count INTEGER;
BEGIN
  -- Period: yesterday 00:00 UTC to today 00:00 UTC
  v_period_start := date_trunc('day', NOW() - INTERVAL '1 day');
  v_period_end := date_trunc('day', NOW());
  v_digest_code := 'DIGEST-' || to_char(v_period_start, 'YYYY-MM-DD');

  -- Skip if already exists
  IF EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM hash_registry_digests WHERE digest_code = v_digest_code)
  THEN RETURN NULL; END IF;

  -- Build manifest of all packets generated in the period
  SELECT
    jsonb_agg(
      jsonb_build_object(
        'packet_code', packet_code,
        'packet_hash', packet_hash,
        'generated_at', generated_at
      ) ORDER BY generated_at
    ),
    COUNT(*)
  INTO v_manifest, v_packet_count
  FROM evidence_packets
  WHERE generated_at >= v_period_start AND generated_at < v_period_end;

  IF v_packet_count = 0 THEN
    v_manifest := '[]'::jsonb;
  END IF;

  -- Compute Merkle root (simplified: hash of concatenated sorted hashes)
  -- For production, use a true Merkle tree library; this is placeholder
  SELECT encode(
    sha256(convert_to(
      coalesce(string_agg(elem->>'packet_hash', ':' ORDER BY elem->>'packet_hash'), ''),
      'UTF8')),
    'hex')
  INTO v_merkle_root
  FROM jsonb_array_elements(v_manifest) elem;

  INSERT INTO hash_registry_digests (
    digest_code, period_start, period_end, packet_count,
    merkle_root, hash_manifest, digest_hash
  ) VALUES (
    v_digest_code, v_period_start, v_period_end, v_packet_count,
    v_merkle_root, v_manifest,
    encode(sha256(convert_to(
      v_digest_code || '::' || v_merkle_root || '::' || v_packet_count::text,
      'UTF8')), 'hex')
  )
  RETURNING id INTO v_digest_id;

  RETURN v_digest_id;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql SECURITY DEFINER;

-- Schedule: daily at 01:00 UTC (2 hours before retention expiry,
-- so packets about to expire are safely digested first)
SELECT cron.schedule(
  'daily-hash-digest',
  '0 1 * * *',
  $$ SELECT generate_daily_hash_digest(); $$
);
4.2 — Edge Function: publish-digest-to-storage
After a digest row is created, an Edge Function publishes it as a static JSON file to Supabase Storage (or equivalent public object store). The URL becomes the permanent external anchor.
FUNCTION: publish-digest-to-storage
TRIGGERED BY: A database trigger on hash_registry_digests INSERT, or
              scheduled via pg_cron 10 minutes after digest generation

STEP 1 — Load the latest unpublished digest
STEP 2 — Serialize to canonical JSON:
  {
    "digest_code": "DIGEST-2025-01-15",
    "period_start": "2025-01-14T00:00:00Z",
    "period_end":   "2025-01-15T00:00:00Z",
    "packet_count": 47,
    "merkle_root":  "a3f...",
    "hash_manifest": [ ... ],
    "digest_hash":  "9e1...",
    "produced_at":  "2025-01-15T01:00:00Z",
    "produced_by":  "EvidenceLedger",
    "verification_instructions":
      "Compute SHA-256 of any Evidence Packet's packet_hash and locate it
       in hash_manifest. Presence confirms existence as of period_end."
  }
STEP 3 — Upload to /digests/DIGEST-2025-01-15.json (public bucket)
STEP 4 — Update hash_registry_digests:
  UPDATE hash_registry_digests SET
    published_at = NOW(),
    public_url = 'https://[STORAGE_DOMAIN]/digests/DIGEST-2025-01-15.json'
  WHERE id = [digest_id];
  (This UPDATE is permitted only via SECURITY DEFINER function.)
🔒 WHY DAILY DIGESTS BEAT PER-PACKET ANCHORING
Publishing every packet hash individually would create scaling problems and provide no better cryptographic guarantee. A daily digest with Merkle root provides:

• Constant-cost anchoring regardless of packet volume
• Compact external reference (one URL per day, not one per packet)
• Cryptographic proof of inclusion via Merkle path (future extension)
• Natural batching for any optional blockchain anchoring

Daily granularity means a packet generated at 23:59 may wait 1-25 hours to be anchored. This is acceptable: the retention window is measured in months, so a one-day lag is negligible.


SECTION 5 — EVIDENCE PACKET EXPORT (Self-Contained PDF)
Per DOCTRINE-030, the exported PDF is the AUTHORITATIVE content carrier after retention expiry. It must be self-contained, cryptographically verifiable without network access, and usable by anyone with basic SHA-256 tooling.
5.1 — PDF Structure (Complete Specification)
The PDF generator (which exists in skeletal form from Part #1) must produce a document containing:
•	Cover Page: EvidenceLedger logo, Packet ID, Session ID, Facility name, ‘Generated at’ timestamp, and a prominent verification banner with the packet_hash in large monospace type.
•	All Evidence Packet Sections 1–9 (or 1–10 if related sessions exist per Part #4): Exhibit Identification, Actor Authority, Event Record, System Actions, Current Session State, Evidentiary Scope & Limitations, Verification Statement, Contextual Delay Events (from Part #3), Session Closure Declaration (from Part #4), Related Sessions (if applicable, from Part #4), Evidentiary Summary.
•	Verification Instructions Page: embedded instructions for verifying the PDF’s integrity using open-source tools. Must include: the packet_hash, the session_hash, the pdf_hash (self-referential — hash of the PDF excluding this field, computed via a canonical method), step-by-step verification procedure, and fallback URLs for the daily digest anchor.
•	QR Code: encoding the packet_hash and verification URL, for quick scanning by external verifiers.
•	Metadata Footer on every page: Packet ID, page number, hash truncated to first 16 chars (for visual identity check between pages).
5.2 — Verification Instructions (Embedded in PDF)
This text must appear on the Verification Instructions page of every exported PDF:
