  - Use a deterministic renderer (same input → byte-identical output)

STEP 5 — Compute PDF_HASH (canonical)
  - The PDF contains a self-referential field where its own hash appears.
  - To handle this: render PDF with placeholder '{{PDF_HASH}}', compute hash
    of that intermediate PDF, then perform in-place byte replacement of
    the placeholder with the hash value. The canonical PDF_HASH is the
    hash of the intermediate PDF (BEFORE the placeholder is replaced).
  - This resolves the self-reference paradox.

STEP 6 — Update evidence_packets metadata
  UPDATE evidence_packets SET
    last_exported_at = NOW(),
    export_count = export_count + 1
  WHERE packet_code = [input];
  -- This UPDATE is the ONE permitted column mutation on evidence_packets,
  -- via SECURITY DEFINER function. Content columns remain immutable.

STEP 7 — Return PDF bytes + metadata
  { pdf_bytes: [Buffer], pdf_hash: '...', packet_hash: '...',
    digest_url: '...', exported_at: '...' }
ℹ THE PDF HASH SELF-REFERENCE PROBLEM
A PDF cannot contain its own hash without the hash changing when the hash is inserted. The standard solution (used here) is:

1. Render PDF with a placeholder string (e.g., 32 spaces where the hash would go).
2. Compute SHA-256 of this ‘pre-insertion’ PDF. Call this CANONICAL_HASH.
3. Byte-replace the placeholder with CANONICAL_HASH in the PDF.
4. The PDF now contains its own CANONICAL_HASH.
5. Verifiers are instructed: ‘To verify, replace the hash field with 32 spaces, then compute SHA-256. Compare to the hash printed in the PDF.’

This is slightly more complex than naive hashing but is the ONLY way to produce a self-verifying PDF. Implement it carefully and test thoroughly.


