⚠ FINAL DOCTRINE GATE — PART #5
Before presenting any code, run this mental checklist:
(1) Does the retention worker delete content BEFORE creating the tombstone? If yes → SEVERE VIOLATION of the tombstone ordering principle. FIX IMMEDIATELY.
(2) Can a human role — even an admin — trigger retention expiry manually? If yes → FIX. (DOCTRINE-005 and 028: system_lifecycle_worker only)
(3) Can a human role restore, recover, or undelete tombstoned content? If yes → CATASTROPHIC VIOLATION. No mechanism may exist. (DOCTRINE-028 non-reversibility)
(4) Does the tombstone table preserve any content beyond hashes and minimal metadata? If yes → FIX. (DOCTRINE-029: no event content, no timestamps beyond tombstone, no actors)
(5) Can verification WORK after retention expiry without any EvidenceLedger contact? If no → FIX. Path A must work with only PDF + digest + SHA-256. (DOCTRINE-033)
(6) Does the exported PDF include embedded verification instructions? If no → FIX. (DOCTRINE-030)
(7) Is the PDF’s self-hash computed via the placeholder-replacement pattern correctly? If implemented naively (hashing PDF containing its own hash), verification will be broken. Test rigorously.
(8) Does any API accept a request to ‘restore’ or ‘recover’ tombstoned content? If yes → REMOVE. No such endpoint exists.
(9) Does the system claim to provide CONTENT after tombstoning? If yes → FIX. Only hash lookup is possible. (DOCTRINE-032)
(10) Is pg_cron configured for BOTH daily-hash-digest (01:00 UTC) and retention-expiry-daily (03:00 UTC)? If no → FIX. The 2-hour gap ensures packets are anchored before expiry.


